description: From Middle English snowte, snoute, from Middle Dutch or Middle Low German snute (alternatively spelled snuut, snuyt), from Proto-West Germanic *snūt, from Proto-Germanic *snūtaz.
Compare Saterland Frisian Snuute, Dutch snuit or snoet (“snout; cute face”), German Schnauze, Schnute. Doublet of snoot.

entries.meaning: The long, projecting nose, mouth, and jaw of a beast, as of pigs.
examples: The pig rooted around in the dirt with its snout.

entries.meaning: The front of the prow of a ship or boat. [First attested in 1387.]

examples: His glasses kept slipping further down onto his prominent snout.

entries.meaning: The nozzle of a pipe, hose, etc.
examples: If you place the snout right into the bucket, it won't spray as much.

entries.meaning: The anterior prolongation of the head of a gastropod; a rostrum.
The anterior prolongation of the head of weevils and allied beetles; a rostrum.

examples: (Bob, p. 55:) Charlie was the most vicious screw on the block ... He caught me with the two ounces of snout right in my hand, caught me by the hair, and swung me round in the exercise yard ...
(Spider, p. 175:) She brings me snout and sweets, and sometimes a cake from Mum.

entries.meaning: A butterfly in the nymphalid subfamily Libytheinae, notable for the snout-like elongation on their heads.

verbs.description: snout (third-person singular simple present snouts, present participle snouting, simple past and past participle snouted)

entries.meaning: To furnish with a nozzle or point.
